[[Image:Brazilianfestivalparticipants.JPG|thumb|150px|right|A [[Brazil | Brazilian]] man dressed in the [[costume]] of a buffoon]]

The term '''Buffoon''' is a (usually) friendly term for someone who provides amusement by his appearance or behaviour or both. Etymology is of the old Italian "buffare" meaning to puff out one's cheeks. [[Robin Williams]] conjectures in the movie ''[[Toys]]'' that the word "is a combination of the words 'buffer' and 'fool.' Or perhaps 'buffamotus,' he who carries the pickle."

Strictly, a buffoon is, "A ridiculous, but nevertheless amusing person" and is often used to upbraid naughty school children, e.g. "Stop that Master Tisshaw - you are a buffoon".

Examples of buffoons in the US would be [[George W. Bush]] and in the UK would be such people as [[Boris Johnson]], or [[Andy Crane]] - both of whom are held in popular regard but who nevertheless engender amusement with their pronouncements and acts. An example of this type of behaviour is when Johnson memorably admitted publicly that he had forgotten the title of his own book as he was writing it, hence an inconsistency between the wording on the hard cover ("Jottings From The Stump") and the dust jacket ("Jottings On The Stump"). The popular press has also branded [[John Prescott]] as a buffoon although he is not held in the same affectionate regard as the above.

A "tired and emotional" [[John Wilmot, 2nd Earl of Rochester | Earl of Rochester]] was involved in an amusing incident in a poem presented to the king, when he said:

: ''Poor Prince''
: ''Thy prick, like thy buffoons at Court'':''Will govern thee because it makes thee sport''

